:"Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","Fifeshire, Scotland, Dalgety":"Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","Aberdeen, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Aberdeen, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pattersone","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and northern English: variant of <b>Patrickson</b> ‘son of   Patrick  ’, which was either shortened to <i>Patrison</i> and metathesized to <i>Patterson</i>, or shortened from <i>Paterickson</i> to <i>Patterson</i>.","Irish: in Ulster, this name is of English or Scottish origin, but in County Galway, it was also taken by bearers of the Gaelic name <b>Ó Caisín</b> ‘descendant of the little curly-headed one’ (from Gaelic <i>casín</i> ‘curly’), which is usually Anglicized as <b>Cussane</b>. In addition to the confusion between Irish Gaelic <i>casín</i> ‘curly’ and <i>cosán</i> ‘path’, there has also been an erroneous assumption that the English name <i>Patterson</i> is somehow derived from the English word <i>path</i>.","English: 19th-century variant of <i>Patteson</i>, a shortened form of   Pattinson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Patteson","meanings":["Scottish, northern English, or Irish: variant of   Patterson  ."]},{"name":"Patrick","meanings":["Irish, Scottish, and English (of Norman origin): from the Anglo-Norman French, Middle English, and Older Scots personal name <i>Patrick</i> (Old Irish <i>Patraicc</i>), derived from Latin <i>Patricius</i> ‘son of a noble father, member of the patrician class’. This was the name of a Christian saint, a 5th-century Romano-Briton who became the apostle and patron saint of Ireland, and it was largely as a result of his fame that the personal name was so popular from the Middle Ages onward. In Ireland the surname is usually Scottish in origin, from Scottish settlers in Ulster in the 17th century. See also   Peden   and   McPadden  , derived from pet forms of Old Irish <i>Patraicc</i>.","Scottish and Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Scottish and Irish Gaelic <b>Mac Phádraig</b> ‘son of Patrick’.","English: variant of   Partridge  ."]},{"name":"Paterson","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Patterson  ."]},{"name":"Paddison","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of <b>Pattison</b> (see   Patterson  ) with voicing of intervocalic /t/ to /d/."]}]},{"name":"Jonnet","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Either a simplified spelling of   Jeannette   or a revival of a medieval pet form of the female name   Jean ."],"variants":[{"name":"Jeannette","meanings":["diminutive form of <i>Jeanne</i>, feminine form of <i>Jean</i> ‘John’, now also used in the English-speaking world."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jonnet Pattersone was born in 1504, in Aberdeen, Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Walter Pattersone, was 35 and her mother, Marie Brok, was 29. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with James Eglinton Steinsone. She died about 1555, in her hometown, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1504–abt 1555":"1504–umbes 1555","1504–1555":"1504–1555","1505–1555":"1505–1555","1525–Male":"1525–Surnud","1530–Female":"1530–Surnud","1530–Male":"1530–Surnud","1470–Male":"1470–Surnud","1475–1510":"1475–1510","1525":"1525","abt 1555":"umbes 1555","1555":"1555","1510":"1510","about 1525":"umbes 1525","1530":"1530","1475":"1475","1470":"1470","abt 1530":"umbes 1530","1505":"1505","1504":"1504","Aberdeen, Scotland":"Aberdeen, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Fifeshire, Scotland, Dalgety":"Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Aberdeen, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Aberdeen, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1504–abt 1555":"1504–noin 1555","1504–1555":"1504–1555","1505–1555":"1505–1555","1525–Male":"1525–Kuollut","1530–Female":"1530–Kuollut","1530–Male":"1530–Kuollut","1470–Male":"1470–Kuollut","1475–1510":"1475–1510","1525":"1525","abt 1555":"noin 1555","1555":"1555"